State Comptroller Report: The actual budget for most years of the Medicare Basket committee  is less than the recommended budget
According to the report by Matthew Engelmann, for more than 20 years of the Hassle activity, the Ministry of Health did not supervise the activities of the committee.
The report also states that the minutes of the meetings are published with substantial delay, if at all.
The evaluator also recommends increasing the transparency of the sub-committee's work and updating the procedures for the work of the basket.
Another deficiency found concerns the fact that since the commission began operation, the Ministry of Health has not asked the hospital funds for reports on the extent of use and utilization of the drugs in the database  which would allow to analyze and control the budget allocated to them.
The Drug Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees in our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new medicines that will be given to the public free of charge through the hospital funds. But a new report by the State Auditor published today (Tuesday) warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without being monitored and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council monitored and investigated its activity.
Israel Today reporter Ren Reznik adds that the state complainant was investigated following Israel Today's ongoing disclosures of drug cartels.
According to the report by Mathieu Engelman, he recommends "reforms and improvements in the expansion of the basket, leading to a better utilization of the health care basket budget to which the public is entitled".
Over the years of the existence of the drug basket supplement mechanism, in the years 2021-1998 drugs were added to the state budget for a total of eight billion NIS, with the supplement moving annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million NIS.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add some 800 new drugs and technologies to the health care basket, with a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated to the expansion of the basket was less than the scope of the requests.
For most of the commission's tenure (90% of the time), the size of the budget surcharge was less than 1.5% of the health care basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired surcharge rate.
The critic points out that the annual supplement needs to be examined and adjusted in order to allow certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model of basket work is lacking".
For example, the ESC's working procedure stipulates that the minutes of meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 160-109 days, while sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in publication of protocols impairs the transparency of decisions; therefore, it may harm the ability of bidders  patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies  to re-apply as soon as is practicable and relevant, after having learnt lessons from their bids that were rejected, analysed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and revised their bids and reevaluated their re-admission to the next round", the reviewer stated in the report.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols according to the timeframes established in the protocol".
Out of thousands of submissions, only one economic comment was submitted.
Another criticism of Engelman concerns the preliminary process of assessing technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The reviewer found that half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the postponement.
Another discrepancy concerns the activities of the Medicine Basket subcommittee, which is closed to the media and the public and in which patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The critic recommends attaching a public representative or exploring the possibility of making the discussions public without commercial details that are confidential.
The policy under which the Health Care Board operates is that "a financial assessment must be submitted" for a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic evaluation has been submitted out of thousands of submissions and the commission makes its decisions without a financial evaluation.
For example, the 2021-2019 Basket Committee hearings were requested to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report found that economic calculations were not added to the requests, including an estimate of the amount that could be saved by reducing the harms of obesity-related disease or by being able to avoid gastric bypass surgery.
It also appears that the decisions of the Medicines Basket Committee are inconsistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and evaluation for the treatment of cancer in chronic diseases as targets, but in the framework of decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The critic also warns that since 2011, the medication basket also includes services that are not the responsibility of the hospital funds, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, given by the Ministry of Health ("The Third Supplement").
That's when the legal framework for this step is only loosely regulated.
For the last six years, NIS 74 million from the pharmacy fund has been used for these services.
Engelmann recommends that the Health Ministry update the basket work protocols and also determine if a separate surcharge is required for these services.
About a third of the new drugs coming into the marketplace are defined as "no-cost drugs", which don't cost the patient extra money because they replace existing treatment.
The critic proposes to study the possibility of these drugs being administered in a different and shorter route, so that the drug basket can be updated several times a year rather than just once a year.
There's no control over the use of very expensive drugs.
The audit also shows that since the Basel Committee started its work 20 years ago, the health ministry hasn't required the health funds to report nor monitored the extent of use and utilization of Basel medicines, information that would have allowed the office to analyze and control the budget allocated to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports relating to the years 2009-2006 were published, and these were also published late (the last one was published in the year and dealt with the use of the budget for the years 2009-2007).
