Professor Galia Rahab, head of the infectious diseases unit at Sheba.
On the Professor Marvin Shapira and others.
The Encounter That Opened My Eyes - And Changed My Life
If I hadn't met Professor Marvin Shapira, Sr., who was the director of the infectious disease unit at Hadassah, I probably would have remained an internal medicine physician.
He's the one who got me interested in the field of infectious disease and got me into it.
I met him in the corridors of Hesse, back in the '80s.
For a moment, I didn't think that I would be leaving Internite, because I loved patient care itself; but Professor Shapira showed me that the field of infectious disease was also expressed in neurology, internite, in fact, in all areas.
I thank him for bringing me into this field.
All along, I loved his investigative approach, an approach that gets to the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor with all his soul, who loved his patients and taught me not to take things for granted and to examine everything thoroughly.
He was a real, honest, selfless man, qualities that I appreciated very much.
At first, when I was asked to choose the doctor who was my role model and greatest influence, I meant to choose my father, Dr. Joseph Rekber, Sr., a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who influenced me to go into medicine -- but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapira.
Both, for example, prompted catchphrases that doctors still use today - such as "Tisu is de persona", in which a biopsy of tissue from an infected organ indicates which drugs to give; or "Whenever you use too much, use too little", which explains that overuse of antibiotics causes the bacteria to become resistant.
Professor Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked in engineering and father of two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family at seven, I cried.
He was something -- a smart, smart epidemiologist who volunteered for anything.
He never complained, even during his illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the epidemic response team, and he's sorely lacking at this time.
If he was with us today, I'm sure I would have consulted with him, and I'm sure he would have been one of the leaders of the epidemic response team.
