Medical negligence in the various stages of childbirth
To get compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that the damage was caused by the same negligence.
Birth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in a family's life.
Yet, unfortunately, sometimes births end in serious birth or birth-related injuries as a result of the negligence of medical personnel.
In cases where the birth resulted in physical injury to either the child or the mother, there is scope to examine the chain of events that led to the injury and even to consider seeking legal advice.
A medical malpractice lawyer will examine if there were defects in the medical staff conduct at the various stages of birth that caused the injury, and, if deemed appropriate, will consult a medical specialist in the relevant field.
It should be stressed that not every error in care on the part of the medical staff amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily teach that its management was negligent.
When is it negligence?
Where the doctor's error resulted from incompetence or deviation from reasonable care, and the incompetence and deviation from accepted care caused harm to the patient that otherwise would not have been caused by the doctor.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of childbirth, explain what complications may occur at each stage, and when they may amount to medical negligence.
Axial phase
The fusion phase lasts an average of 8 to 14 hours.
During this phase, the cervix gradually opens (to allow for the passage of the fetus at birth) and eventually should reach a diameter of about four inches [10 cm].
Most cases of miscarriage involve failure to recognize fetal distress prior to birth, which has resulted in damage to the unborn, sometimes resulting in cerebral palsy.
Paralysis of the brain:
Cerebral palsy can be caused by misidentification or delay in identifying congenital breastfeeding, which is manifested as failure to deliver oxygen to the fetal brain tissue.
In general, monitoring the condition of the newborn, and proper deployment of the fetal heart monitor should lead to early detection of developing fetal distress, allowing the medical team to act quickly and rescue the newborn before it is irreversibly harmed.
Cases where the medical staff ignore signs of oxygen deprivation in the fetus or do not correctly interpret the data in it, especially the fetal monitor, or respond with delays to the distress displayed on the monitor  may be negligence.
Cerebral palsy can also be caused by a dislocated umbilical cord as well as an undetected uterine tear.
Even in these extreme events, it's worth asking whether the medical team acted properly.
For example, Anna Reiff Liganza, an attorney with the law firm of Crouch & Co. specializing in representing medical malpractice victims, explains that her office handled a child who was injured during birth after a midwife blocked the amniotic sac when the fetal head was too high, resulting in the fall of the umbilical cord (when the umbilical cord is in advance of the fetal head) and impaired oxygen supply to the fetal brain (caused by pressure from the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and his child being born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, a lawyer testified that her office filed a complaint for gross medical negligence against the staff of the maternity ward of a large hospital who during the delivery failed to identify on time obvious signs which prompted a genuine suspicion that the newborn had suffered a rupture of the uterus in the area of the surgical scar of the previous pregnancy.
The fetus that escaped through the rift in its mother's uterus to the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until its late discharge when it was on the verge of death.
Due to severe fetal distress during his birth, the child was born with a complex neurological disability.
We insist, that in order to win damages, the plaintiffs prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal relationship between the negligence of the medical staff which led to the failure to identify the lactating woman and the damage to the newborn, which means that the damage was caused by said negligence and not by any other cause or factor.
Causal association analysis will be performed by examining medical parameters whose existence is the only one in the medical literature that provides a causal link between the concussion and the brain injury.
Among other things, the fetus' blood acidity measurements, its blastocyst scores, the presence of neurological and systemic damage, and more.
Death of the fetus
The active stage of labor
The active stage of labor begins when the cervix opening reaches four inches in diameter and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical phase.
Birth defects and the avoidance of cesarean section
In some cases, a dysfunctional birth develops, a lack of progress of the active birthing process.
In such cases, it is customary to perform a Caesarean section, in order to prevent various possible injuries to the fetus due to delayed delivery.
"In some cases, failure to perform a C-section on time could cause irreversible damage to the fetus", explained lawyer Reiff-Ligonza.
"For example, we had a medical malpractice claim for the death of her infant caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to all known medical practice, the medical staff was not trained to recognize fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite the extremely slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the operation caused extensive systemic damage to Lilouda which eventually led to her death shortly after birth".
Negligence in the birth of a vacuum
In situations where the mother or fetus is exposed to significant danger that requires a particularly rapid termination of the birth, a vacuum birth is sometimes performed.
This process involves attaching a vacuum dome to the fetus' head and forcibly pulling the fetus out.
Naturally, this involves dangers that can cause harm to both the fetus and the child. It requires great care, precision, and skill.
In these events, medical malpractice may be manifested in the fact that the doctor does not follow the mandatory instructions and carries out the operation despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or carries out the operation for too long, or when despite the failure of several attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the operation more than the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases if the negligent vacuum operation has caused birth defects - among others it could have resulted in brain damage and bleeding that may have resulted in the development of brain damage - there is room for a claim for damages.
Paralysis on the ERB name
Paralysis after birth, here is congenital nerve damage in the cervical spine, when it occurs during childbirth, it's worth checking to see if the damage was due to the negligence of the delivery team.
The injury manifests in weakening of the muscles of the hand and can extend to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in delivering the newborn due to a "breech disorder" - a birth emergency that occurs when the fetus's shoulders become trapped inside the birth canal after its head is released.
When should you suspect that the paralysis was caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the weight of the fetus is assessed as macrosome, meaning it is expected to weigh more than 10 pounds (4.5 kg) at birth and in accordance with the guidelines, it is better to deliver the mother via cesarean delivery.
When the birth weight is over 10 pounds, a C-section should be considered in light of the risk factors including gestational diabetes and prolonged stage two labor.
In the event that the medical team ignores an abnormal fetal weight or other risk factors and opts for a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder dislocation and ERB-related paralysis becomes a reality, there is a strong possibility of medical negligence.
Indeed, in H.R. 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk of shoulder dislocations occurring during childbirth may be predicted with varying degrees of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder dislocations when they are suspected is by cesarean section".
The stage of the placenta
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to uterine contractions after the child's exit and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process usually lasts up to half an hour after the baby is delivered and occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the discharge, the medical team will check to see if she's out safely or if any parts of her placenta are left in the uterus.
At this stage, complications can occur that could cause serious damage to the fetus.
One of the most common complications of an absent cervix is known as "Ashman's syndrome" or a uterine laceration that results from inflammation caused by an absent cervix, which damages the lining of the uterus in a way that prevents pregnancy.
So in cases where the medical team failed to identify that the remains remained or failed to take all necessary steps to prevent cervical mutilation despite a suspicion of the remnants in the uterus, this could be a case of medical negligence and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer.
Death in childbirth
The death of a mother during childbirth is a fairly rare occurrence.
In these cases, the event that should have brought happiness and joy to the family turns, sadly, into the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical staff fails to detect bleeding in the birth mother at the time or responds late to the bleeding.
"For example", explained lawyer Raef-Lignanza, "our office has filed a lawsuit concerning the death of a newborn, in which the medical team ignored and failed to respond to the distressing vital signs of the newborn for several hours after a diagnosis of a massive, uncontrollable bleed occurring as a known complication of her underlying condition".
"In another case", said Attorney Reif-Ligonza, "our firm represented the relatives of a woman who died after giving birth to twins due to bleeding from an improperly sutured c-section.
In the same case, the woman complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical team did not address her complaints and her clinical condition adequately, responding delayed only after her body systems had begun to collapse, which led to her death".
Loss of uterus
In severe cases, medical negligence in childbirth may lead to a hysterectomy. Attorney Rafe Lingiza says: "Our law firm sued a hospital that performed a hysterectomy due to medical negligence after birth.
In that case, the delivery woman, a young woman of 31, lost her uterus due to inadequate treatment of the massive bleeding observed by the medical staff after childbirth and yet not taken timely actions that could prevent the damage".
What are the damages awarded for medical malpractice at birth?
Maternity compensation for injury due to medical negligence at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being awarded for pain and suffering, nursing and salaried care, loss of salary and pension for the injured and even for his parents and other damage components.
The compensation to the injured minor for lost wages and pension is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average wage in the economy.
Also, the compensation includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation equipment, the cost of accommodation for the baby's needs, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation was determined in any case for his body and according to his circumstances", said attorney Reif-Ligenza, adding that "today most medical malpractice claims are settled in a compromise that weighs the chance and risk that each party has in conducting the procedure", but added that "there are cases where the proceedings end only in a verdict, after which if the case is not dismissed the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damage and for example, in a case conducted by our office, the district court ruled that a youngster who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in treatment will receive compensation in excess of ten million shekels".
In conclusion
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly every family's nightmare.
In these cases proper legal examination of the chain of events that led to the tragic outcome, by a lawyer trained in handling medical malpractice claims, can help you get the compensation you deserve.
It's the reason for the prevalence of keratoconus eye disease in the South.
Research has suggested that there is a connection between the development of the disease and consanguineous marriages
The highest incidence was found in the Bedouin sector.
Expert: "It may be that in any area with a lot of cousin marriage there is a high incidence of the disease".
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes some visual impairments.
It's very important to diagnose it early, and find the right solutions to prevent it from getting worse.
In recent years, some studies have been conducted to understand how the disease develops, and new treatments have been developed.
The new research gives scientific basis to suspect that Keratoconus eye disease is a genetic disease.
A recent study of the transformation of the cornea from dome to cone found that the cause of corneal disease, and of corneal weakness and deformation, is related to an enzyme imbalance, whereby free radicals can damage corneal proteins and change the structure of the cornea.
The source of that enzyme deficiency is genetic, a fact that supports the hypothesis that keratoconus is an inherited disorder.
According to Prof. Ariyal Gordon-Shag, head of the Department of Optometric Sciences at the Hassa Academic College, "In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, the prevalence of keratoconus was found to be 3.2%.
The highest prevalence was among students from the Bedouin sect - 20% had karatokonos, but there was a relatively small sample".
The researcher added that it is not a surprising finding: "Cartoconus is widespread in the Bedouin community.
In our studies, we found that close marriages are a risk factor for cartoconus.
So in any sector with a lot of cousin marriages, you may find a high incidence.
In this context it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unambiguous conclusion: In cases where a family history of keratoconus disease appears, all family members should undergo an appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Erza Procter, a B.Sc. clinical optometrist, "there is ten times more clinical outreach from the peripheral areas, especially from the south, than the center".
Proctor adds that "Over the last decade, I have noticed that most of the patients are moving away from the periphery, especially the Beersheba area.
This is mainly due to high rates of inter-family marriage (mostly in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of the correct treatment of the problem".
So how do you diagnose the disease?
Prokter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or late teens (ages 16-15, or 20).
This disease involves a decrease in vision, parallel to an increase in the cylinder.
Cartoon-conus patients exhibit distorted and/or blurred vision of figures and bones.
These signs get worse with the progression of the disease, which often develops slowly and gradually over years.
However, the disease can also progress rapidly and reach a peak in just a few months.
Many of the patients even report increased sensitivity to light.
