Research shows that Zoom meetings hurt creativity.
Some 2,100 engineers and academics around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem  some in videoconferences, some in face-to-face meetings
The result: Virtual meeting hurts creativity and thinking outside the box.
The lead researcher at Columbia University: "Visual focus on the screen hurts the process of creation of ideas"
There's no loss of productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature looked at the effect of video conferencing on participants' creativity, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, we find that creativity is indeed hurt in virtual meetings through screens.
The question for the study -- led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University -- was whether remote computer meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming meetings, or do creativity and freethinking decline as a result of the distance.
The study itself started back in 2016 but got a big boost in the two years of the coronavirus, when many employees moved to work from home.
"People in a face-to-face meeting move around the room, using objects, and being helped to think creatively", says Brooks.
"In a computer session, on the other hand, the focus on keeping eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative brain activity.
Visual focus on the screen impairs cognition.
"People are more focused on video when interacting, which impairs the larger, expansive thought process".
Space is shrinking.
To test the results and see if they would repeat themselves, they were tested twice -- once at Columbia University and again in real life -- on engineers who knew each other from early on.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two halves -- one, they were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to a problem, and the other, they were asked to do it through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide themselves similarly and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, there was a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who met virtually.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher into ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study, but wasn't surprised by the results.
He thinks that in thinking activity, people usually look at their environment for a source to help generate ideas, whereas in video conferencing, thinking goes to the screen and doesn't expand in a creative way.
"When people in the same room look around and see the space, there are objects and situations that can trigger new associations in them.
On the contrary, research shows that interacting through the computer changes our attention so that we are more focused on the inside and the screen, and this way reduces innovation and generates ideas through looking at the environment and thinking outside".
There's no harm in critical thinking.
However, before managers rush workers back to the office, the researchers note that "computer work did not hurt productivity itself or people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, where they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
That is, the damage is focused only on creativity and not on other forms of computer work".
Professor Ellen Langer, a psychology professor at Harvard University, is also covering the findings.
She says, "There's a difference between just being creative, like new uses of Prisby, and working solutions.
It may also be that when employees are more relaxed after the introduction, or work from home, creativity does improve".
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also proposed a future study in which such meetings would be limited to thinking and wandering the room to see how this activity would affect the end result.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study only the brainstorming meetings would allow employees back to work, and as a general rule, he suggested not to be frightened by one study but to make another inquiry in this area.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forcibly returned and be unhappy. "That's a bigger insult", he says.
