By 2050, the world will lose 80 percent of the water available for agriculture
A new global study predicts a significant decline in the next 25 years •
The Solution: Proper Management of Water
A disturbing new study recently published in the journal Earth's Future, predicts that by 2050, the amount of water available for agriculture will decline by about 80 percent if the world's water consumption and population growth rates stay on present trends.
In the study, which involved scientists from all the world's science agencies, scientists pooled the total amount of rainwater, rivers and freshwater sources in the world and compared it to humanity's agricultural needs.
The grim findings show that right now the rate of water use is doubling over and over in the last 10 years, while global warming is causing fewer rains in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the study, 84 percent of the world's arable land will experience a severe shortage of rainwater.
One of the key conclusions of the study calls on farmers around the world to adapt agriculture to climate and seasonal changes, and to switch to farming methods that take into account the water permeating the land to avoid water evaporation that leads to widespread rainwater waste.
The researchers also recommend that farmers working near saltwater sources use rainwater harvesting technologies to prevent it from flowing into the sea.
