Among other things, customers' payment accounts were exposed over a significant period of time, and those accounts included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, vehicle location, travel dates and times.
Moreover, since the transit company did not legally document access to its systems, it is not possible to know precisely for how long unauthorized agents have been able to access the company's systems.
In the letter of violation, forwarded to the company by the Privacy Protection Authority, the Authority stressed that most of the large companies and organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that with the development of threats and risks, the organization is obliged to carefully examine the updated risks and to act accordingly with the updating of the security measures accepted in the circumstances, depending on the nature of the database and its utility.
As a result, companies and organizations are required to update their systems and conduct risk assessments and penetration tests, to examine and assess the changing risks.
Companies and organisations are also required to use an automatic recording mechanism and training is required for employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy (Information Security) Regulations.
In accordance with the findings of the Supervision, the Authority determined that the company had violated the provisions of the Privacy Act and its regulations and required the company to take a number of corrective actions.
"The matter has been handled according to the strictest requirements".
